body:
Deep in IceNet, there's a snippet of verilog that looks like this:

```verilog
    string devname = "";
    int rlimit_gbps = 64;
    byte rlimit_inc = 1;
    byte rlimit_period = 1;
    byte rlimit_size = 8;
    int dummy;

   // ...

    initial begin
        dummy = $value$plusargs("netbw=%d", rlimit_gbps);
        dummy = $value$plusargs("netburst=%d", rlimit_size);
        dummy = $value$plusargs("netdev=%s", devname);
        network_init(devname, rlimit_gbps, rlimit_inc, rlimit_period);
    end
```
—https://github.com/firesim/icenet/blob/7c17985a46108c8ff8d424b1b3af6eebc37c38a3/src/main/resources/vsrc/SimNetwork.v#L68-L73

When verilated,  `+netdev=...` wasn't getting picked up on the command line, and I couldn't find any writes to the `devname` variable anywhere. On a hunch, I changed the block to:

```
    initial begin
        dummy = $value$plusargs("netbw=%d", rlimit_gbps);
        dummy = $value$plusargs("netburst=%d", rlimit_size);
        if ($value$plusargs("netdev=%s", devname))
            $display("using devname=%s", devname);
        network_init(devname, rlimit_gbps, rlimit_inc, rlimit_period);
    end
```

And the devname was indeed assigned from the plusarg. To me, this looks very similar to https://github.com/verilator/verilator/issues/3131 —the optimizer isn't "seeing" that the plusargs call changes devname, and so can't be removed without changing the meaning of the program.

Verilator version:
```
$ verilator --version
Verilator 5.022 2024-02-24 rev conda-forge build 0
```
I haven't tried the latest from git; if you think it's likely to make a difference I'll give it a shot.

What OS and distribution are you using? Arch Linux

May we assist you in trying to fix this in Verilator yourself?

Sure, I'd be happy to give it a shot: I assume the fix would be somewhat similar to 08c8b0d7d655d2c8afe91114818e2e943bc8a601 , if you can point me towards the rough area of the optimizer that's deleting the AST nodes when they're writing to a never-read variable.
